Meta-Painting, 2019-2023
Series of diamond shaped painting done by nanopolymer material that is normally used to search cancer cell in human body.
It is not a pigment based color spectrum but a strucured color specifically combined by its chemical forms. This is a result of the collaboration with Cornell Nano Lab run by Uli Wiesner. This color doesn't fade overtime, and is the same color structure we see in the butterfly wing. Ever since I have been inspired by nano polymer and it's magic, and our major collaboration made a first architectural scale of [A Needle Woman- Galaxy was a Memory, Earth is a Souvenir] 14 m high outdoor sculpture using the polymer together with Uli Wiesner'S nano lab and his post doctorate students at Cornell Univ., and with an architect Jaeho Chong. This pieces has been commissioned under direction of Staphanie Owen's for the CCA biennale of Cornell Uiv. We  continue to experiment different possibilities of the aestethics of Nano polymer for the Metz Cathédrale stained glass pieces and these are from that experiments. Due to the viewing distance and the nature of old cathédrale that has historical and conventional stained glass panels, this has not been used at the end but I decided to show them as Meta-Painting. It is the first and the only painting in history made of structural color (not pigment) generated by nano-material.

Sky 01.27.2023 Puerto Escondido

Announcing Meridiano, a new gallery situated on the Oaxacan coast in Puerto Escondido, Mexico, opening in February 2023.

Expanding the possibilities of the traditional gallery model, Meridiano offers an open framework for long-form, site-specific, and experimental exhibitions of new work by artists working internationally and across disciplines. Founded by Nicholas Olney and Boris Vervoordt on the principles of dialogue and exchange, Meridiano’s contemporary art programming will be realized over two exhibitions per year, beginning with Kimsooja (b. 1957; Korea) 자오선 Jaoseon (Meridian) from February – July 2023.

Photo: Diego Flores

Invitée par les Galeries Lafayette, l’artiste sud-coréenne @kimsoojastudio présente To Breathe : une installation artistique qui révèle l’architecture du grand magasin par la lumière. Pour l'occasion, l'artiste habille le dôme de la Coupole historique d'un film qui diffracte la lumière et inonde l'espace d'arcs-en-ciel. À découvrir à partir du 25 avril au magasin Coupole des Galeries Lafayette Paris Haussmann.

📍Terrasse & magasin Coupole, Galeries Lafayette Paris Haussmann.
🕘 Du 14 avril au 30 juin 2023, expérience exclusive de To Breathe dans l'entre-deux coupole : dates et horaires sur haussmann.galerieslafayette.com 

Invited by Galeries Lafayette, the South Korean artist
@kimsoojastudio presents To Breathe: an art installation that reveals the architecture of the Department Store through light. For the occasion, the artist designed a dome of the historic Coupole with a film that diffracts the light and floods the space with rainbows. See you in store until June 30th at Galeries Lafayette Paris Haussmann.

Nella sua performance “A Needle Woman”, l’artista Kimsooja inscrive il proprio corpo, verticale e immobile, in mezzo al tumulto di alcune megalopoli e di zone interessate da conflitti politici. Come una forza resistente e pacificatrice, Kimsooja è un ago che simbolicamente permette di intessere relazioni tra individui e reinventare un tessuto sociale.⁣
⁣
Scoprite l’installazione video a Punta della Dogana nella grande mostra #Icônes⁣
⁣
Info e prenotazioni su palazzograssi.it⁣
-⁣
Through the performance “A Needle Woman”, Kimsooja inscribes her body in its verticality and immobility, amid the tumultuous flows of the megalopolis and zones of political conflict, as a resisting, pacifying force, a needle making it symbolically possible to weave relations between individuals, to recreate a social fabric, a possible proximity.⁣
⁣
Discover the video installation at #PuntadellaDogana in the great Icônes exhibition.⁣
⁣
Curated by Emma Lavigne in collaboration with Bruno Racine.

During Berlin Art Week, Kimsooja and Elisabeth Millqvist presented our new publication 'SOWING into Painting'. This book unveils the essence of Kimsooja's transformative 2020 exhibition at Wanås Konst in Sweden. 

Co-published by The Wanås Foundation and Kewenig, this meticulously crafted publication offers a profound exploration of Kimsooja's groundbreaking vision. The exhibition invites viewers to delve into a world where painting transcends conventional boundaries. This catalogue serves as a visual and interlectual companion, shedding light on the intricate layers of Kimsooja's approach, featuring an interview with Elisabeth Milquivist(@elisabethmigiv), along with a forward by Milena Hoegsberg(@milena_hoegberg). 

The installation 'Meta-Painting', which originated at Wanås Konst, is currently on display at our gallery Berlin-Mitte.

‘Thing are already there, already existing. We just don’t know, we just don’t discovered them’ – Kimsooja

With her current exhibition at our gallery in Berlin, the artist focuses on traces of processes, of time, of material and on how such transformations are perceived individually. With the works in the exhibition, Kimsooja refers to her idea about the dissolution of boundaries and the interpretation of different levels, spatially or temporally. The simultaneity of materiality and immateriality can be experienced in each go Kimsooja’s works in this exhibition, but also in the totality of this spatially comprehensive presentation.

repost via @instarepost20 from @sevresmanufactureetmusee L'exposition Deductive Object : Bottari met en lumière le travail de l’artiste Kimsooja créé en collaboration avec les artisans de la Manufacture. 

🌔 A Sèvres, Kimsooja, artiste sud-coréenne, a transformé le bottari (un sac traditionnel coréen) en moonjars (ou « jarres de lune », un vase traditionnel coréen) en le figeant dans de la porcelaine ou de la terre cuite. 

Le bottari est pour Kimsooja un symbole de l'exil et du voyage qu’il implique. Contenant parfois les souvenirs d’une vie, il se vide ici pour représenter les corps de ceux qui les portent. 

🪡 Pour l’œuvre "Sewing into Soil:  Invisible Needle / Invisible Thread", elle perce des plaques de grès avec une aiguille, créant une constellation de trous qui incarnent l'énergie de la nature. 

DEDUCTIVE OBJECT : BOTTARI | KIMSOOJA
📅 A partir du 9 octobre

<Deductive Object-Bottari 1999-2019> just arrived to Humbolt Forum in Berlin as part of <Kimsooja, (Un) Folding Bottari> exhibition from Poitier. The container enveloped the artist's personal belongings during her 20 year living in New York and transported to Poitier in 2019 as part of Traversées exhibition in France which coinsided with her departure from New York. The Artist painted the container with Obangsaek color which is known as a cardinal color spectrum in Taoism, Confuscionism, Buddhism, and Shamanism which is rooted in Korean and Ural altaic linguistic countries. 

This exhibition unfolds Kimsooja's various evolution on Bottari concept spanning from her earlier sewn piece to the most recent commission work <Deductive Object-Bottari, 2023> which Kimsooja conceptualizes the Korean traditional Moonjar as Bottari, in collaboration with Meissen Pocelain Manufacture. Juxtaposing across the collections of Asisian Art Museum and Ethnological Museum in Humbolt Forum, this parcours invites audiences to the artist's life long investigation on the notion of canvas and its evolution and how life and art continue an intricate discourse in her career.

Last weekend to see the exhibition ‘Meta-Painting’ by @kimsoojastudio at our gallery @keweniggalerie in Berlin- Mitte. 

The term 'Meta-Painting' is to be understood in a similar way to the relationships underlying a meta-language. It is about painting that is not executed. It is about painting that negotiates painting without the need for paint. It is the non-doing that, in the spirit of John Cage, nevertheless produces a perceptible result, which thereby acquires a conceptual, spiritual depth.

All this is accompanied by the incessant breathing of the light installation 'To Breathe'. The rhythm of inhaling and exhaling, which here corresponds to the rhythm of the course of the day and the path of the sun, permeates the interior spaces with ephemeral but recurring, ever-changing, iridescent plays of light. The breath is not audible, but can be experienced visually and spatially. Kimsooja succeeds here in an impressive way in transferring the physical function, which can at the same time have a meditative function, to a building, to the people who move around in it and are invited to contemplate.

repost via @instarepost20 from @galleriaraffaellacortese Kimsooja's coloured prisms are part of the group show "EMOTION: contemporary art tells emotions", now on view at Chiostro del Bramante, Rome. 

"Truth is never a destination but a long and winding journey that cannot exclude mistakes and deceptions. Every truth is accompanied by its own deception, Abel by his Cain, every existence by its original sin. Truth and Deception are siamese brothers that cannot be separated, and art is the measure of their comparison. It is the artists who act in this territory, and they are the ones who ignite the thrill of emotion. Emotion is a dense and unexpected dialogue between truth and appearance, it is the sign of a confrontation guided by surprise and emotion." - Danilo Eccher, curator. 

The artists on display look for answers to questions such as: How many emotions inspire an artist? And how many are held within the artwork? What emotions does a spectator feel in front of that artwork? Do they endure over time, or do they change?

repost via @instarepost20 from @humboldtforum At the invitation of the Museum für Asiatische Kunst, the artist Kimsooja together with guest curator Keumhwa Kim has developed a sequence of (non-)interventions in the permanent exhibitions. In 'Kimsooja – (Un)Folding Bottari', existing works and new pieces created especially for the exhibition connect associatively with the historical objects in the museums’ galleries, stimulate dialogues and place collections and their themes in a relationship to the present.

Bottari, sculptural objects made of richly coloured textiles, are a characteristic motif of Kimsooja’s work and are both material and metaphor. They stand for protective reception as well as for unfolding and offering. In cooperation with the Staatliche Porzellan-Manufaktur Meissen, a new group of porcelain works related to Bottari was created especially for the exhibition.

Take a look on your next visit to the Humboldt Forum! The exhibition is on view until 19 February 2024, in the ethnological and Asian art galleries on the third floor.
.
Auf Einladung des Museums für Asiatische Kunst hat die Künstlerin Kimsooja gemeinsam mit der Gastkuratorin Keumhwa Kim eine Abfolge von Sammlungsinterventionen entwickelt. In der Ausstellung 'Kimsooja – (Un)Folding Bottari' verbinden sich ältere und eigens für die Ausstellung neu entstandene Werke assoziativ mit den historischen Objekten in den Galerien der Museen, regen Dialoge an und setzen Sammlungen und ihre Themen in ein Verhältnis zur Gegenwart.

repost via @instarepost20 from @art Kimsooja (@kimsoojastudio) is a South Korean conceptual and multidisciplinary artist whose work, particularly exemplified by “A Needle Woman,” holds profound significance in contemporary art. Known for her exploration of themes such as identity, displacement, and the human condition, Kimsooja often uses her own body as a powerful symbol. “A Needle Woman,” a pivotal piece in her oeuvre, captures the artist standing still amidst bustling urban environments in various global cities. Through this repetitive yet poignant act, Kimsooja raises questions about the individual’s place in a rapidly changing world, the transience of time, and the tension between the self and the surrounding chaos. The work becomes a meditation on the universality of the human experience, emphasizing both the vulnerability and resilience of the individual within the vast tapestry of contemporary life. Kimsooja’s “A Needle Woman” invites viewers to reflect on their own existence, prompting a deeper understanding of the interconnectedness that binds humanity across cultures and geographies.
